item.title: Getting Started: Part 1: Verifying your Installation
item.description:
About

Before you begin, it is a good idea to verify your installation and make sure Nuix REST is up and running. You can easily do this by using the /v2/about endpoint.

The unauthenticated version of this endpoint will only return the server and serverId fields. All other fields will be null and require an authentication token to view them.

Request Response 
curl --location --request GET 'http://localhost:8080/nuix-restful-service/svc/v2/about'

{
    "server": "http://localhost:8080",
    "serverId": "nuix-restful-server-1",
    "startupTime": null,
    "nuixRestfulVersion": null,
    "engineVersion": null
}

item.title: Getting Started: Part 2: Verifying your Licenses
item.description:
Licensing

Prior to consuming endpoints from the Nuix RESTful Service, it is important to have your licensing properly configured. You can check if your license server has been properly configured by invoking the /v1/licenses endpoint. This endpoint does not require authentication.

item.title: Getting Started: Part 3: Authentication
item.description:
Authentication

Now that you know your server is properly installed and configured, the first thing you will want to do is authenticate.

Request Response 
curl --location --request PUT 'http://localhost:8080/nuix-restful-service/svc/v1/authenticatedUsers/login' \
--header 'Content-Type: application/json' \
--header 'Accept: application/json' \
--data-raw '{
	"username":"username",
	"password":"password",
    "licenceShortName": "enterprise-workstation",
    "workers": 2
}'

{
    "username": "username", 
    "authToken": "9729a460-eda7-48dc-ba70-d12b3aae3c8d",
    "licenseShortName": "enterprise-workstation",
    "workersGranted": 2
}

Note

The licenceShortName and workers fields in the request body are optional. If they are excluded any license will be selected and 1 worker will be granted.

Note

Please note the authToken field returned in the response will need to be submitted in the nuix-auth-token request header field on all subsequent requests.

You have now successfully authenticated to Nuix RESTful Service!

item.title: Getting Started: Part 4: Case Creation
item.description: Nuix supports four types of cases. These are Simple, Compound, Elasticsearch, and Compound Elasticsearch cases. In this section, we will demonstrate how to create these case types.

item.title: Getting Started: Part 5: Ingestion
item.description:
Ingestion

For the purposes of this example, we are going to use the following request to ingest the Nuix Engine documentation that is distributed as part of the Nuix RESTful Service installation. After performing the request, an asynchronous function key will be returned which can then be polled for status.

Request Response 
curl --location --request POST 'http://localhost:8080/nuix-restful-service/svc/v1/cases/43b070164ce8453ca30ed9e2dfcce67b/evidence/file' \
--header 'nuix-auth-token: 9729a460-eda7-48dc-ba70-d12b3aae3c8d' \
--header 'Content-Type: application/json' \
--header 'Accept: application/json' \
--data-raw '{
   "processorSettings": {
   	"storeBinary": true
   },
   "target": {
    "path": "/Engines/9.0.0.171/doc"
  }
}
'

    "location": "http://localhost:8080/nuix-restful-service/svc/v1/asyncFunctions/814388bb-d0fe-4a75-a4cb-02d1f46213e2"
}

item.title: Getting Started: Part 7: Exclusions
item.description:
Exclusions

As part of the culling process, it is sometimes necessary to exclude items from your case. For this example, let’s exclude all Javascript files (*.js) from the case using the excludedItems endpoint.

Request Response 
curl --location --request PUT 'http://localhost:8080/nuix-restful-service/svc/v1/cases/43b070164ce8453ca30ed9e2dfcce67b/excludedItems' \
--header 'nuix-auth-token: 9729a460-eda7-48dc-ba70-d12b3aae3c8d' \
--header 'Content-Type: application/json' \
--header 'Accept: application/json' \
--data-raw '{
  "excludeDescendants": true,
  "includeDuplicates": true,
  "includeFamily": true,
  "includeNearDuplicates": true,
  "nearDuplicatesThreshold": 0,
  "query": "file-extension:js",
  "reason": "Exclude script files from the case"
}'

{
    "functionKey": "575f4966-1103-43fb-b6bb-03f52b7b3022",
    "location": "http://localhost:8080/nuix-restful-service/svc/v1/asyncFunctions/575f4966-1103-43fb-b6bb-03f52b7b3022"
}

Verifying Exclusions

Let’s verify the items have been excluded from the case using the search endpoint.

Note

item.title: Getting Started: Part 8: Item Sets and Deduplication
item.description:

An item set is a collection of items that have been classified as originals or duplicates based on whether there are multiple items with the same hash value. item.title: Getting Started: Part 9: OCR
item.description:
In this example, we will ingest the Nuix logo below into our case and perform Optical Character Recognition (OCR) on it. Right click on the image in your browser to save the image to disk as nuix.png.

Verify OCR Capability

In order to perform an OCR, the OCR plugin from https://download.nuix.com/releases/addons needs to be installed. To verify that the OCR plugin is installed call the resources/ocr endpoint.

Request Response 
curl --location --request GET 'http://localhost:8080/nuix-restful-service/svc/v1/resources/ocr' \
--header 'nuix-auth-token: 9729a460-eda7-48dc-ba70-d12b3aae3c8d'

{
    "success": true
}

File Ingestion of Image

Next, let’s ingest our image with text.

Request Response 
curl --location --request POST 'http://localhost:8080/nuix-restful-service/svc/v1/cases/43b070164ce8453ca30ed9e2dfcce67b/evidence/file' \
--header 'nuix-auth-token: 9729a460-eda7-48dc-ba70-d12b3aae3c8d' \
--header 'Content-Type: application/json' \
--header 'Accept: application/json' \
--data-raw '{
   "processorSettings": {
   	"storeBinary": true
   },
   "target": {
    "path": "/Images/nuix.png"
  }
}
'

item.title: Getting Started: Part 14: Clustering
item.description:
Clustering

Nuix REST supports clustered installations to enable distributed workloads across multiple nodes within a cluster. When configured as a cluster, requests submitted to Nuix REST are managed and distributed across the cluster with no further action from the user.

Note

Only Elasticsearch Cases are supported by cluster mode.

For more information about configuring your Nuix REST instances for clustering please see the clustering guide
